<h2>HVAC Systems in Michigan</h2>

<h3>Climate Considerations</h3>
<p>Michigan's continental climate demands HVAC systems capable of handling both extreme cold and hot, humid conditions. Winter temperatures frequently drop below freezing from December through February, with some areas experiencing temperatures as low as -10¬∞F to -20¬∞F. Summer temperatures typically range from 75¬∞F to 85¬∞F with high humidity levels, creating substantial cooling loads. This climate profile requires heating systems that can operate efficiently in sub-zero conditions and cooling systems rated for high humidity environments.</p>

<p>For heating, Michigan homeowners should consider systems with Annual Fuel Utilization Efficiency (AFUE) ratings of 90% or higher for furnaces, or Heating Seasonal Performance Factor (HSPF) ratings of 8.5 or higher for heat pumps. Cold-climate heat pumps have become increasingly popular in Michigan, as modern units can operate efficiently down to -15¬∞F while providing both heating and cooling capabilities. For air conditioning, SEER ratings of 16-18 are recommended to balance efficiency with cost-effectiveness in Michigan's moderate cooling climate.</p>

<p>Humidity control is particularly important in Michigan due to the Great Lakes' influence on regional weather patterns. Whole-house dehumidification systems or HVAC units with enhanced humidity control features help maintain indoor comfort while reducing energy consumption. Proper insulation and air sealing are critical in Michigan homes to maximize HVAC efficiency, as the significant temperature differentials between indoor and outdoor conditions can lead to substantial energy losses without adequate thermal barriers.</p>

