<h2>Michigan Incentives & Rebates</h2>
<p>Michigan offers several attractive incentives for solar and HVAC upgrades that significantly improve the return on investment for homeowners. The most substantial benefit is the federal solar Investment Tax Credit (ITC), which allows homeowners to deduct 30% of solar installation costs from their federal taxes through 2032. This credit applies to all system components including panels, inverters, mounting hardware, and installation labor, with no cap on the credit amount. The credit can be carried forward to future tax years if it exceeds current tax liability.</p>

<ul>
<li><strong>Federal 30% Solar Tax Credit:</strong> Available through 2032, this credit reduces to 26% in 2033 and 22% in 2034 before expiring for residential installations. The credit covers the full cost of solar panel systems, battery storage, and installation expenses.</li>
<li><strong>Property Tax Exemption:</strong> Michigan provides a property tax exemption for solar energy systems, meaning the added home value from solar installation doesn't increase property tax assessments. This exemption applies to both the equipment and installation value.</li>
<li><strong>DTE Energy Solar Incentives:</strong> DTE offers net metering programs allowing customers to receive credit for excess solar energy sent to the grid. The utility also provides rebates up to \$500 for solar water heating systems and energy efficiency upgrades.</li>
<li><strong>Local Utility Rebates:</strong> Many Michigan utilities offer additional rebates for high-efficiency HVAC systems, with amounts ranging from \$200-1,000 depending on equipment efficiency ratings and system types.</li>
<li><strong>PACE Financing:</strong> Property Assessed Clean Energy (PACE) financing is available in many Michigan counties, allowing homeowners to finance solar and energy efficiency improvements through property tax assessments with up to 25-year terms.</li>
</ul>

